I. About
========

  This file explains how to compile and use the primesieve console
  (terminal) application. If you rather want to compile the primesieve
  GUI application please refer to src/qt-gui/INSTALL. If you want to
  build primesieve as a library for use in your own C++ program please
  refer to doc/LIBPRIMESIEVE.

  Precompiled binaries for Windows, Linux and Mac OS X are available
  at: http://code.google.com/p/primesieve/downloads/list

II. How to build primesieve
===========================

  Unzip the primesieve source archive, open a terminal or 'Visual
  Studio Command Prompt' and cd into the newly created directory. Now
  use one of the following make commands to build primesieve using
  your favorite C++ compiler:

  $ make                     Default `c++' compiler (GNU make)
  > nmake -f Makefile.msvc   Microsoft Visual C++

  Other C++ compilers:

  $ make CXX=g++   CXXFLAGS="-O2 -fopenmp"
  $ make CXX=icpc  CXXFLAGS="-O2 -openmp"
  $ make CXX=sunCC CXXFLAGS="-O5 -xopenmp"
  ...

  Optionally you can install primesieve using (as root):

  $ make install

III. Target a specific CPU
==========================

  You can indicate your CPU's L1 data cache size in kilobytes per
  core to get the best performance. For MSVC use e.g.:

  > nmake -f Makefile.msvc L1_DCACHE_SIZE=64

  On Linux and Mac OS X this is done automatically.

IV. How to use it
=================

  $ cd bin
  $ ./primesieve 10000           Count the primes up to 10000
  $ ./primesieve 10000 -p1       Print the primes up to 10000
  $ ./primesieve 1e5 2e5 -p2     Print the twin primes within [10^5, 2*10^5]
  $ ./primesieve 1e9 -o1e5 -c2   Count the twin primes within [10^9, 10^9+10^5]
  $ ./primesieve --help          Print the help menu
  $ ./primesieve --test          Run various sieving tests

  For Windows use primesieve.exe instead of ./primesieve
